---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Introduction to Claude Code"
  description="An introduction to Claude Code — an agentic AI assistant that can read, write, and run code on your behalf — and the ideas that make it work."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cc-intro">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Introduction to Claude Code</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          An agentic AI assistant with hands and feet — letting anyone, even without programming
          experience, build the tools they need through plain language.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: What is Claude Code -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">What is Claude Code?</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The AI tools we are familiar with (such as early ChatGPT or Gemini) are like a
        "library without hands or feet": you ask a question and it gives you an answer, but you
        still have to copy, paste, and run everything yourself. Claude Code, on the other hand,
        is more like a <strong>personal AI assistant with hands and feet</strong>. It is
        <strong>agentic</strong>, which means it not only chats with you but can also take action
        on its own. It can directly read files on your computer, modify them, run commands, and
        even open a browser to test the result for you.
      </p>

      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="compare-card compare-card--muted">
          <p class="compare-label">Traditional AI chat tools</p>
          <p class="compare-title">A library without hands or feet</p>
          <p class="compare-desc">
            It can only answer questions — you still have to copy, paste, and run things yourself.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card compare-card--accent">
          <p class="compare-label">Claude Code</p>
          <p class="compare-title">A personal assistant that can act</p>
          <p class="compare-desc">
            It reads files, edits them, runs commands, and verifies results — carrying a task
            through from start to finish.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The best part is that you do not need to know how to code. With Claude Code, anyone can
        simply describe what they want in natural language (a <em>prompt</em>), and the AI will
        plan and build the web page or small tool on its own. This new style of development is
        often called
        <span class="tech-tag inline-tag">Vibe Coding</span>.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 2: Agentic Loop -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">How Claude Code Works</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Claude Code is powerful because it combines two core elements: a
        <strong>brain (the AI model)</strong> and <strong>hands and feet (tools)</strong>. When
        you give it a task, it repeatedly runs through a three-step process known as the
        <em>agentic loop</em>:
      </p>

      <ol class="loop-list">
        <li class="loop-step">
          <span class="loop-num">1</span>
          <div class="loop-body">
            <h3 class="loop-title">Gather Context</h3>
            <p class="loop-desc">
              When you describe a task (for example, "help me fix this bug"), Claude Code
              automatically looks for the relevant files to read, or searches the web, to first
              understand the current situation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="loop-step">
          <span class="loop-num">2</span>
          <div class="loop-body">
            <h3 class="loop-title">Take Action</h3>
            <p class="loop-desc">
              Once it understands the context, it plans what to do and then edits files,
              creates new ones, or runs system commands to carry out the plan.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="loop-step">
          <span class="loop-num">3</span>
          <div class="loop-body">
            <h3 class="loop-title">Verify Results</h3>
            <p class="loop-desc">
              This is where it really shines. After making changes, it runs tests on its own to
              check whether the approach actually worked. If something is still wrong, it reads
              the error messages and goes back to step one to correct itself, repeating until
              the problem is solved.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <!-- Section 3: Four Power Features -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Four Features That Make Claude Code More Powerful</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        To help this assistant understand you better and work more efficiently, Claude Code
        comes with a few useful advanced features. Think of them as different tools a colleague
        might keep at their desk:
      </p>

      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">01</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">CLAUDE.md</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">The personal handbook</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            A memo file kept inside the project. You can write down your team's design
            conventions, your personal preferences, or your typical workflow. Claude Code reads
            this handbook before it starts working, so it will not forget your rules and you do
            not have to repeat them every time.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">02</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">MCP</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">The plug-in cable</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            Short for <em>Model Context Protocol</em>. Think of it as a USB cable: once you
            connect the right MCP, Claude Code can reach external services — read your Gmail,
            check your Google Calendar, or write notes into Notion — so it can, for example,
            prepare your daily briefing automatically.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">03</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Skills</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">Specialist skill packs</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            When the "handbook" gets too long, the AI can become distracted by the sheer volume
            of information. Standard procedures that are only needed occasionally (such as how
            to build a slide deck or how to draw a diagram) can be packaged as a
            <em>skill</em>. Claude Code only opens the pack when a related task comes up,
            keeping its focus sharp and its responses efficient.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">04</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Subagents</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">AI helpers</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            For a large task that requires gathering a lot of information, Claude Code can spin
            up dedicated helpers. Each helper goes off to do its own research and grunt work,
            then reports the key findings back to the main Claude — saving you a great deal of
            waiting time.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 4: Which entry point? -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Should I pick Desktop, VS Code, or the CLI?</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        When people first encounter Claude Code, the most common sticking point is not
        "can I use it?" but rather "where should I even start?" The three entry points are not
        ranked by skill level — they are simply three different ways of working:
        Desktop is like opening a ready-to-use app; VS Code is like bringing Claude into the
        editor you already work in; and the CLI is like working alongside Claude directly in the terminal.
      </p>

      <div class="entry-grid">
        <!-- Desktop -->
        <article class="entry-card">
          <div class="entry-header">
            <span class="entry-index">1</span>
            <h3 class="entry-title">Desktop</h3>
            <p class="entry-tagline">The closest thing to "just open it and start"</p>
          </div>
          <p class="entry-desc">
            Think of Desktop as the entry point that requires the least warm-up.
            Download, install, sign in, and you can start using Claude Code right away on your desktop.
            For first-time users, the biggest advantage is not that it has more features,
            but that <strong>the barrier feels lower</strong>: you do not need to understand the terminal first,
            and you do not need to move your workflow into an IDE.
            Just open Claude, let it help you with something small, and that is already a great start.
          </p>
          <p class="entry-fit-label">A good fit when</p>
          <ul class="entry-fit-list">
            <li>You are new to Claude Code and want to get started in the most intuitive way.</li>
            <li>You would rather not touch the terminal right away.</li>
            <li>You want to try small tasks first — reading a folder, explaining a file, organizing content.</li>
            <li>What you need is "just start using it," not "understand the full dev environment first."</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="entry-desc">
            Desktop feels a bit like inviting an AI assistant to sit beside you —
            it watches with you, works with you, and you gradually get comfortable with how it operates.
            It is not the most engineering-oriented entry point, but it is usually the easiest first step to take.
          </p>
          <div class="entry-transition">
            <p class="entry-transition__label">When might you want to move beyond Desktop?</p>
            <p class="entry-transition__body">
              When you start needing to browse a file tree, edit code, and check diffs all at the same time,
              or when you already spend most of your time inside VS Code,
              switching to the VS Code integration usually feels smoother.
              This is not because Desktop is not good enough,
              but because your way of working starts to look more like "ongoing collaboration inside a project."
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- VS Code -->
        <article class="entry-card">
          <div class="entry-header">
            <span class="entry-index">2</span>
            <h3 class="entry-title">VS Code</h3>
            <p class="entry-tagline">The closest thing to "plugging Claude right into your workspace"</p>
          </div>
          <p class="entry-desc">
            If Desktop is like inviting Claude in, VS Code is like installing Claude directly into the place
            where you already work. You are already browsing files, editing content, and switching folders in VS Code —
            putting Claude Code in the same window usually makes the whole flow feel more natural.
          </p>
          <p class="entry-fit-label">A good fit when</p>
          <ul class="entry-fit-list">
            <li>You already use VS Code on a regular basis.</li>
            <li>You want to view source files and talk to Claude side by side.</li>
            <li>Being able to clearly see before-and-after diffs matters to you.</li>
            <li>You often point Claude at specific files, folders, or code snippets to work on.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="entry-desc">
            The advantage of VS Code is not that it "looks more professional" — it is that
            <strong>the switching cost is very low</strong>. Because your files, editor, and chat panel
            are all in the same place, it is easier to understand what Claude changed
            and easier to jump in with a quick follow-up like: "don't change it that way — try a different approach."
          </p>
          <div class="entry-transition">
            <p class="entry-transition__label">Who tends to enjoy VS Code the most?</p>
            <p class="entry-transition__body">
              If you are not entirely put off by technical tools but also do not want to start
              with a pure terminal, VS Code is often a comfortable middle ground.
              It keeps the intuitiveness of a graphical interface while letting you work directly inside your project.
              For people who maintain websites, codebases, or file collections over the long term,
              this tends to be the most stable primary entry point.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- CLI -->
        <article class="entry-card">
          <div class="entry-header">
            <span class="entry-index">3</span>
            <h3 class="entry-title">CLI</h3>
            <p class="entry-tagline">The closest thing to "working in Claude Code's native space"</p>
          </div>
          <p class="entry-desc">
            CLI is the terminal version. For some people, seeing a terminal feels intimidating;
            for others, it is the most direct, cleanest, and least roundabout way to work.
          </p>
          <p class="entry-fit-label">A good fit when</p>
          <ul class="entry-fit-list">
            <li>You are already comfortable with the terminal.</li>
            <li>You like typing commands, running them, and seeing output directly.</li>
            <li>Your workflow leans toward shell-based tooling.</li>
            <li>You plan to explore more advanced, engineering-oriented usage later.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="entry-desc">
            The strength of the CLI is usually not that it is "flashier" — it is that it is
            <strong>direct</strong>. You do not need to open another large interface or navigate to
            an editor sidebar first; you can jump straight into Claude Code's interactive flow.
            For people already familiar with the terminal, that directness feels comfortable.
            Claude Code can read codebases, edit files, run commands, and integrate with dev tools
            as an agentic coding tool — and the terminal is a very natural home for that kind of work.
          </p>
          <div class="entry-transition">
            <p class="entry-transition__label">When is the CLI not the best starting point?</p>
            <p class="entry-transition__body">
              If you are still unfamiliar with what a terminal even is, or if your real goal right now
              is to understand how Claude Code collaborates with you,
              there is usually no need to force yourself to start with the CLI.
              It is not that the CLI is bad — it is that it asks you to face two new things at once:
              Claude Code itself, and the terminal as a way of working.
              For many people, that makes the first step feel heavier than it needs to be.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .cc-intro {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Compare cards (library vs assistant) */
  .compare-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  .compare-card {
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .compare-card--accent {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .compare-label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .compare-card--accent .compare-label {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .compare-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .compare-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Inline tag inside paragraph */
  .tech-tag {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-1) var(--space-3);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 500;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .inline-tag {
    vertical-align: baseline;
  }

  /* Agentic loop steps */
  .loop-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-4);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }

  .loop-step {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .loop-step:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    transform: translateX(4px);
  }

  .loop-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 2.5rem;
    height: 2.5rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .loop-body {
    flex: 1;
  }

  .loop-title {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .loop-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Feature cards grid */
  .feature-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }

  .feature-card {
    position: relative;
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .feature-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    box-shadow: 0 4px 12px var(--color-card-shadow);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .feature-index {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .feature-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
  }

  .feature-alias {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-3);
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
  }

  .feature-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Entry-point cards (Desktop / VS Code / CLI) */
  .entry-grid {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }

  .entry-card {
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .entry-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .entry-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-4);
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
  }

  .entry-index {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 1.75rem;
    height: 1.75rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .entry-title {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
  }

  .entry-tagline {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
  }

  .entry-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .entry-desc strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .entry-fit-label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .entry-fit-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
  }

  .entry-fit-list li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .entry-fit-list li::before {
    content: '✓';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .entry-transition {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-8);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
  }

  .entry-transition__label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .entry-transition__body {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Mobile */
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .compare-grid,
    .feature-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .loop-step {
      gap: var(--space-4);
      padding: var(--space-6);
    }

    .loop-num {
      width: 2rem;
      height: 2rem;
      font-size: var(--text-sm);
    }

    .entry-card {
      padding: var(--space-6);
    }

    .entry-transition {
      padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    }
  }
</style>
